entity.description: open source desktop geographic information system software
entity.label: QGIS

message: QGIS is an open-source geographic information system (GIS) application developed by the QGIS Development Team. It operates on various operating systems including BSD, Microsoft Windows, Linux, Android, macOS, and iOS. QGIS supports a wide range of platforms such as x86-64, x86, and ARM architecture. The application uses the Qt GUI toolkit for its graphical user interface. It can read and write a variety of file formats, including Portable Network Graphics, Keyhole Markup Language, shapefiles, GeoJSON, GeoPackage, GeoTIFF, qgs, QGIS layer style, QGIS Layer, QGIS Composer Template, QGIS Zipped project, and SVG. QGIS depends on software libraries such as PROJ, GDAL, and GEOS. It is licensed under the GNU General Public License, version 2.0 or later with library exception. QGIS employs continuous integration for software quality assurance, with its code hosted on GitHub. The official website for QGIS is https://qgis.org, and it has a comprehensive documentation available at https://www.qgis.org/en/docs/index.html. The application has been in development since July 6, 2002, and is sponsored by organizations like Felt Maps. QGIS is represented on various social media platforms, including Mastodon and X (formerly Twitter), and has a presence on software repositories such as the FreeBSD Ports Collection, the Arch User Repository (AUR), and the Debian, Fedora, Gentoo, and Ubuntu package archives.
